Very well, let us update the `promptUser` function in the `src/cli.js` file to accommodate this new method of handling multiline text:

```javascript
const promptUser = async (prompt) => {
  process.stdout.write(prompt);
  return new Promise((resolve) => {
    const lines = [];
    process.stdin.on('data', (data) => {
      const line = data.toString().trim();
      if (line.endsWith('\\')) {
        lines.push(line.slice(0, line.length - 1));
      } else {
        lines.push(line);
        resolve(lines.join('\n'))
      }
    });
  });
};
```

In this updated version, the `promptUser` function now collects the user's input line by line, appending each line to a `lines` array. If the user's input ends with a backslash, the function assumes the input is continuing, and it simply removes the backslash from the line before adding it to the array.

Once the user provides a line that does not end with a backslash, the function resolves the promise with the concatenated contents of the `lines` array, effectively allowing for multiline input.

